description:
ratelimit.rs:20:
    pub fn new(capacity: u32, window_secs: u64) -> Arc<Self> {
        Arc::new(Self { ... })
    }

What goes wrong: constructors should return Self and let the caller decide the ownership model. Returning Arc<Self> means:
1. The type cannot be used without heap allocation, even in tests or single-owner contexts.
2. Arc::clone() on the return value creates a double-Arc<Arc<RateLimiter>>, which compiles without warning and is functionally correct but wasteful.
3. It's a teaching anti-pattern — if another type in this codebase follows this convention, developers learn "constructors return Arc" and apply it broadly.

AppState already stores inbox_limiter: Arc<RateLimiter>. The wrapping decision belongs at the call site (server.rs:51), not inside new().

Fix: change new() to return Self. Update server.rs to wrap: let inbox_limiter = Arc::new(crate::ratelimit::RateLimiter::new(60, 60));
